My meme

My meme inspiration

From my inspiration meme, I decided to take the meme and use it in a new way. I turned it into a reaction style meme based around an original premise. I also changed the inspiration meme within the new meme to give it a new context by adding a new layer to the image and adjusting the text.

  library(magick)
  
  #Code for setting the base image
  meme_base <- image_read("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/DavidEtte/stats220/main/Project1/inspo_meme.png")%>%
    image_scale(250)
  
  #Code for creating all the blank images and text
  text_base <- image_blank(width = 250, height = 315, color = "#000000")%>%
    image_annotate(text = "Me when fail Stats220",
                   color = "#FFFFFF",
                   size = 20,
                   font = "Comic Sans",
                   gravity = "Center")
  
  text_moustache <- image_blank(width = 250, height = 315, color = "#000000")%>%
    image_annotate(text = "Me when change name
    and live in the bush",
                   color = "#FFFFFF",
                   size = 20,
                   font = "Comic Sans",
                   gravity = "Center")
  
  text_bear <- image_blank(width = 200, height = 50, color = "#333333")%>%
    image_annotate(text = "I'm scared of bears",
                   color = "#FFFFFF",
                   size = 20,
                   font = "Comic Sans",
                   gravity = "Center")
  
  #Setting the image of a moustache to be overlayed
  moustache <- image_read("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/DavidEtte/stats220/main/Project1/Moustache.png")%>%
    image_scale (200)
  
  #creating a vector to store the two images for the first half of the meme
  base_vector <- c(meme_base, text_base)
  
  #combining the two images for the first half of the meme
  meme_top <- image_append(base_vector, stack = FALSE)
  
  #layering the moustache on the base image  
  meme <- image_composite(meme_base, moustache, offset = "+25+100")
  
  #layering new text over the moustache version of the base image
  meme_text <- image_composite(meme, text_bear, offset = "+25+265")
  
  #creating a vector to store the two images for the second half of the meme
  moustache_vector <- c(meme_text, text_moustache)
  
  #combining the two images for the second half of the meme
  meme_bottom <- image_append(moustache_vector, stack = FALSE)
  
  #creating a vector to store the two halves of the meme
  final_vector <- c(meme_top, meme_bottom)
  
  #combining both halves of the meme to make the final result
  meme_final <- image_append(final_vector, stack = TRUE)
  
  meme_final

    image_scale(250)
  
  #Code for creating all the blank images and text

    image_annotate(text = "Me when fail Stats220",
                   color = "#FFFFFF",
                   size = 20,
                   font = "Comic Sans",
                   gravity = "Center")
  
  text_moustache <- image_blank(width = 250, height = 315, color = "#000000")%>%
    image_annotate(text = "Me when change name
    and live in the bush",
                   color = "#FFFFFF",
                   size = 20,
                   font = "Comic Sans",
                   gravity = "Center")
  
  text_bear <- image_blank(width = 200, height = 50, color = "#333333")%>%
    image_annotate(text = "I'm scared of bears",

  #layering new text over the moustache version of the base image

  #creating a vector to store the frames of animation
  animation_vector <- c(text_base, meme_base, text_moustache, meme_text)
  
  #creating the animation
  animation <- image_animate(animation_vector,fps=0.5)
  
  animation
My animated meme

Creativity

For the creativity portion of the assignment I used the magick image_composite function, this allowed me to layer the images on top of one another to create a new image. This is the function that I used to add the mustache and text box onto the original image to create the third panel of the meme

Learning reflection

One thing I learned while doing this module is about the Pros and Cons of linking images vs storing the image within the project. While I found that keeping the image as part of the project was typically faster, easier and more consistently reliable, linking to an externally hosted image was more universal. The externally hosted image would always work the same no matter the context but would suffer from issues like not being able to load due to a bad connection or an issue on the host’s end.

I am curious about learning more applications of RCode graphics creation, creating the meme and animation was the part of the assignment that I enjoyed most and I would like to explore the area some more
